# GitHub Issues — Single Source of Truth

All project issues (bugs, features, improvements) must be tracked in the **GitHub repository** (`vsillah/Portfolio`), not as local markdown files.

## Required behavior

1. **Creating issues:** Use `gh issue create` (via Shell tool) to create issues on GitHub. Do **not** write issue files to `docs/issues/` or any local directory.
2. **Listing issues:** Use the GitHub MCP (`list_issues`) or `gh issue list` to fetch open issues. Do not scan local directories for issue files.
3. **Referencing issues:** Use GitHub issue numbers (e.g. `#34`) when referencing issues in commits, comments, or conversation.

## Labels

Use these GitHub labels for categorization:

- `bug` — Something is broken
- `enhancement` — New feature or capability
- `improvement` — Better behavior for existing functionality

## Shell quoting

When creating issues via `gh issue create`, write the body to a temp file first to avoid heredoc/quoting issues:

```bash
cat > /tmp/gh-issue-body.md <<'ENDOFBODY'
Issue body here...
ENDOFBODY

gh issue create --repo vsillah/Portfolio \
  --title "Issue title" \
  --label "enhancement" \
  --body-file /tmp/gh-issue-body.md
```

## What not to do

- Do **not** create files in `docs/issues/`.
- Do **not** store issue descriptions only in Memory or conversation — always persist to GitHub.
- Do **not** use the GitHub MCP `create_issue` tool (current token lacks write permissions) — use `gh` CLI instead.

## Note on GitHub MCP permissions

The GitHub MCP token (`user-github`) currently has **read-only** access for issue creation. Always use the `gh` CLI for write operations (create, update, close). The MCP can still be used for listing/reading issues.
